segments.text: ...concerning the Vietnam War.
In the interest of accumulating knowledge about the war, I'm going to donate this tape to the Texas A&M Oral History Collection in the University Archives.
Is this alright with you?
Yes.
When and where were you born?
I was born in 1962 at Saigon, South Vietnam.
Do you have any brothers or sisters?
Yes, I do have two brothers.
Are they older, younger?
They're younger than me.
And are they here?
Yes, they're over here.
What are your memories of the old government, of the Saigon government?
What do you remember about it?
Or what do you remember from people telling you when you were young, or your own opinions?
It's not a very good government.
They just wasting the money.
How do you remember the people being treated?
There's two ways to treat people in Vietnam.
differently than the school people.
Like, they had all the lectures?
Yes.
What did your father do?
My father was a teacher.
Oh, like a school teacher?
Yeah, he was a philosophy teacher.
Oh, okay.
Is he here?
Yes, he's over here.
Okay.
So, did your whole family come over?
Yes, my whole family.
What did you think of the American soldiers?
Did you know why they were there?
I mean, what were your feelings about them being there?
Well, I knew they were over here to fight, to help us fight the Communists, but they also bring some very bad influences without exception.
For example?
Like?
Like, uh, prostitution, drugs.
Okay.
So, you say that's why you blame that on the Americans?
You think they started that?
Um, uh, in another way, yeah.
Okay.
Um, why did your family feel they had to leave you?
Did they feel they had no choice?
Yes, we had no choice.
We had to get out because we cannot live with the comrades anymore.
In what year did you leave?
How did you escape?
We escaped on a small boat.
Was it just your family or were you with other people?
It was a small boat and it carried 79 people.
We traveled for seven days on the South China Sea.
And when you say a small boat, like...
It's about 12 yards long, three yards.
And what about food?
What did you eat?
The food supplies only lasted for two days.
And the water, I don't remember, it was about three or four days.
But we survived it.
when we was dropped by the pirates.
They gave us some food and water every time.
What do you mean pirates?
Like the Thailand, the Thai fishmen.
Oh, okay.
They dropped us.
I would think that was pretty scary.
Oh, yeah.
Can you tell me what you felt?
Maybe you think you were going to make it?
Well, when I left Vietnam, Bessie,
Well, I think that, you know, I'm, I'm dead already.
That's only, in ten, in a hundred percent, I only got ten percent, you know, five.
So I wasn't, yeah.
So it's all or nothing?
It's all or nothing, yeah.
Um, was this like all planned out, your escape?
Like, was it?
Yes, it was all playing out because we had to hide it away from the college.
They would bother, they would put us in jail if they know that we tried to escape.
That just seemed so, I bet you were paranoid.
Yeah, our parents planned it, I just don't remember.
But you knew what they were doing, right?
Yeah.
There was a free enterprise restriction in 1978.
There's no free enterprise in Vietnam.
Right, right.
So what were your living conditions?
They weren't too good, were they?
No, the living condition is bad.
How were they compared to before?
Yes, the communists control everything.
Rice is the main food.
And they control it.
And meat, they control it.
Diarrhea and all kinds of that, they will control it.
They will give us an amount each month.
Ration.
Yeah, ration.
And I mean, it wasn't enough.
No, it's not.
How big is your family?
We have five people in our family.
So your parents and your brothers.
But you say they've changed a lot since then, your living conditions.
What do you say?
No, I didn't say they changed.
Oh, you don't think they've changed since then?
No, I don't think so.
It's still that way.
No, I mean now, your own.
Not for the people still in Vietnam.
Oh, right now, over here?
Right, uh-huh.
I mean, you would usually say you have it better now?
Yes, it's better over here in the United States and America.
When you were on the boat, how did you get to America?
Were you planning to get to America?
No, we planned to go to Thailand or Malaysia with our boat because there's some refugee camp over there.
I stayed in refugee camp in Thailand for six months and then I went to the United States.
How did you get to the United States?
So you said your uncle was your sponsor?
How long have you been here?
Since 1935.
Oh, okay.
What were your first thoughts of the United States when you got here?
So big.
Big?
What were you told about the United States before you even knew you were going to be here?
What were your impressions of it?
And do you believe that now since you're here?
Yes.
How have your thoughts changed over time, like about America?
Do you think it's all what it's made out to be?
You know, when people tell you that you can do this and you can go for that.
You know, apple pie, you know?
Well, my thought hasn't changed that much.
Only that I recognize there's some limited to the capitalism.
Can you explain further on that?
Like if you have too much freedom, you can see that the crime strike is going up so much because the prison I didn't get punished.
for the crime that they act, that they commit.
So in Vietnam, they would have gotten?
Yes.
And I think I'm against it.
I don't know why we put so many people on the death row, just wasting tax money to cheat them and have to go through a lot of appeals and appeals and appeals.
I don't know why.
Yeah, I don't understand that either.
It makes me mad too.
Yeah.
I know exactly what you mean.
Yeah.
How have people treated you since you've been here?
Uh, very nice.
Except, you know, one or two occasions that they've been through, but so far, very nice.
Like, so have you experienced racism?
Yes, I have.
Would you say blatantly?
Um, about two years ago or so.
What happened?
It's, uh, I was working in a restaurant and
They wouldn't teach you?
No, I was working and they were a customer.
Oh, you were working then?
Yeah.
And they said something to you?
Yeah, they would all kind of ignore people on the floor.
Oh yeah, that's understand, so you know.
Where did you go to high school?
Okay.
In Vietnam, I went to a high school in Vietnam, and over here I went to Bryan Island.
So you came to Dallas when you got here?
Right away?
Yes.
That's where your uncle goes?
Yes.
How were you treated in high school, among other Canadian students?
Pretty nice.
You were?
That's great.
And so how did you get to A&M?
Yeah, I'd like to get into engineering too, but I won't do anything.
If you were in Vietnam, do you think you'd be going to school?
No.
Engineering degree?
No, no way.
No, not at all?
Not at all.
What do you think you'd be doing?
I don't know.
Go out, find a job, get out of Vietnam as quick as I can.
Just to get out of there, not even stay there.
How are you treated at A&M?
Do you think it's, is it any different in a college atmosphere?
Uh, no.
No.
Okay.
Um, do you feel people stereotype you since you are Oriental background?
Sometimes.
And do you think so more at A&M on a more of an intellectual level?
Do you think they single you out and say, oh, you're Oriental and you're so smart and that's all you ever do is study?
Do you feel that?
No.
No, I don't.
No?
What are your thoughts of Vietnam today when you think about it?
Sad.
Sad?
Would you ever want to go back?
Yeah, I would like to go back if there was no more communists over there.
Do you still have friends over there?
Yes, I do have friends over there.
Do you keep in touch with them?
Not lately.
What's not lately?
Well, since about six months ago, I don't know what happened to them.
All of a sudden?
Yeah, all of a sudden they just stopped.
Probably the stamp price went up too much.
When you did correspond with them, did they say they wanted to leave?
You cannot say it because they will answer on their own.
But did you feel like in their writing that they probably were not happy?
Oh, yes.
What do you think of Americans?
Well, like all the countries, they got good people and they got bad people.
Right.
Do you think...
Americans are forward?
Not really.
You think they're just real curious?
Yes, I'm very curious.
Yeah.
What do you think of, say, American women compared to Vietnamese women?
Do you think that...
They are more material.
American women?
Yeah.
But it's not changing.
The second generation of Vietnamese people over here is... Materialistic as well?
They get Americanized.
Okay, that's what I've been asking.
I'm from Austria.
And that's where I was born.
And I'm an Austrian citizen.
And I've lived here since I was born.
And, you know, people ask me, you know, why don't you get the American citizenship?
Or why, you know, you're Americanized too.
And I say, well...
No, I'm not American.
I'm Americanized.
Do you feel you're Americanized?
Or do you feel... No, I think I'm still...
I'm in an old-fashioned way.
I'm still conservative.
Conservative?
Yeah.
But do you feel you've grown to have more American views than... Well, I've been Americanized, but not as much as other people.
Like what example?
Like about...
What do you think about women working?
Do you think women should work?
Or should stay at home?
No, if a husband cannot support the whole family, the woman should go ahead and help out.
Do you think your views are different than if you had stayed in Vietnam?
Yes, because in Vietnam usually the husband is working, the wife is staying home working.
Well, what if you were in Vietnam and you couldn't support your family?
I wouldn't get married.
You wouldn't get married?
No.
Okay, interesting.
You wouldn't tell your wife to go get a job?
No, I can't.
You can't?
It's against the tradition.
Okay.
Do you want to say something?
Yeah.
How have your goals changed?
Or your values?
Have they changed at all?
Do you have a feeling that you could probably go after it and go for more than if you stayed in Vietnam?
I really don't know.
What are your feelings about
having diplomatic relations with Vietnam now?
Do you think America should and shouldn't, but not?
Yeah, I'm against it.
Why?
Well, because you cannot trust communist people.
You know, in front they will say something, but in the back they will do something else.
They will never keep the promise.
But do you think if there would be diplomatic relations, do you think it would be a better
quality of life for the Vietnamese people?
No.
Because if we have diplomatic relations with the communists, all the people who we get to benefit from it is the top people.
Who are already getting better.
Yeah, they will get better.
Unless, you know, there's no communists, there's no way we can do it.
What's your opinion of Gorbachev?
Well, he's right now, he got a very big trouble because he got the separation of power in the Politburo.
And right now he's trying to eliminate his opponent.
Do you think he means what he says by his blasphemous and perestroika?
Well, he would show off something, but he would not go at it completely.
He would show the free country and say, okay, I'm going to do that.
I'll show you the start, but he would never finish.
I don't really have any more questions, but you've been here eight years now?
Yeah, eight and a half.
And, I mean, you like it here?
It's okay.
It's okay?
College Station's okay, or would you rather be back in...
I would rather be back in Vietnam.
Oh, you would?
Of course, under different circumstances.
What do you miss the most?
A lot of taste in the air.
Like, I'm sure you miss your friends, and... That's one thing.
You miss, like, some of the food, or... Well, food...
I don't know, it's just the feeling that you were born with.
Mm-hmm.
And, uh, it's never go away.
Mm-hmm.
It's still inside you somewhere.
Yeah, it's your home.
Yeah.
Right, yeah.
I don't even know what to say.
Um...
Do you want to be an American citizen?
I am an American citizen.
Oh, you are?
All right.
Yeah, I got the citizenship four years ago.
Oh.
Well, how's that feeling?
How do you feel about it?
Well, not very happy with it.
No, because you had to give up your native language?
Yeah, but I think it's good for me because I can use it to try to do something over here that I'd be able to do.
What do you think about what President Bush, or I guess the election process here?
Do you think it's more of a kind of personality election?
It takes the people who have the best personalities and what they really stand for?
Or do you like the way?
What I think is the media controls too much.
The what?
The media.
The media, oh, definitely.
We get so much information from the media, so we can never tell the truth.
Like, I don't know, they get good qualifications, but somehow we get blow up so much.
Yeah.
You said you're engineering, right?
Yes.
Are you a graduate student now, or are you still your undergrad?
I'm still undergrad.
And when are you finished?
I don't know.
I plan to finish in late 1990.
Do you like that?
That's a good idea, isn't it?
Yes.
You mean you're ready to be finished?
Yes, I'm ready.
Did you know you always wanted to be an engineering major?
Uh, yeah.
I don't know what you're talking about.
Yeah, be a congressman.
A politician?
Yeah, a politician.
Really?
Yeah, I would like to be a congressman.
Really?
If I have a chance.
Uh-huh.
You could go work in Austin.
Work in Austin, you know, in the capital.
Uh, yeah, maybe.
Or you already have bigger...
plans to go right to Washington?
Oh, no, no, that's too big.
Oh, okay.
But right now I just want to get together with some groups, Vietnamese groups, and try to do as much as I can.
What do you want to do?
What do you think needs to be done?
Why should I vote for you if you're going to be a politician?
What would you say with your platform?
platform is, I'm going to reform the judicial system over here.
It's a lot of nonsense in there.
And I would try to speed up the... Not let it sit on death row for so long?
Yeah.
And I would like to speed up the bureaucratic movement.
Like, you have too many departments, too many people.
You have to go
That's a lot of wasting right there.
Thank you.
I agree with a lot of you, actually.
How would it be looked at in your culture or in your family if you were to date an American girl?
Or would you even consider that?
Well, I know my family were against it.
Do you consider that interracial?
Like some people, you know, black and white, they're interracial.
Some people are strongly against that.
Some people don't care.
Yeah, a lot of Vietnamese people are like that.
To me, it's okay.
It doesn't bother you?
No.
Would you do that?
If I can find the right person, right girl.
I know I would find one, but I don't know.
You're not looking for anybody, right?
No.
Do you have a girlfriend now?
Yes, I do.
Vietnamese culture is a different culture than American.
What would you say is the biggest difference?
That if you did date an American girl, what would she have to get used to, do you think?
Vietnamese people are more conservative.
Like, they don't like to see a girl going to the bar and drinking.
Oh, so she wouldn't, she shouldn't do that.
Yeah, and they are against.
But you can do that?
Can you?
Guys, it's okay.
Guys, it's alright.
But the girls can't go do it.
Well, no.
Well, do you think that's kind of unfair there?
I know.
But... You think so?
Yeah.
Oh, okay.
Like, they are against, like, pre-marriage, though, right?
Uh-huh.
Well, I'm sure that's not the statement you'd put for a lot of people.
So, would your family be strongly against you?
Yeah.
Marrying, or?
Do you have anything else that you just want to say?
No, no.
If you have any questions, I'll answer them.
Yeah, I'm trying to think.
Do you think school is tough?
No, no.
If you put, if you determine to go get it, you can get it.
Do you want it bad enough?
How is the school system in Vietnam?
It's more like a French system.
So, like compared to freshman high school together, Vietnam with the American, I think the Vietnam people have more knowledge.
Especially math.
The American people is too, they don't, they don't empathize with the mass.
I guess, Oriental people are always looked at to seem like, it seems like they are very smart and they are very hard workers in their school work.
Are you just brought up from home?
You're going to be doing this so many hours?
We've been doing it in Vietnam.
We have class three days a week.
We have class six days a week.
Saturday, too?
Yeah, Saturday, too.
If I have physics, I have three days a week and one hour, two hours every day, two hours each day.
If you have a lesson on Monday, you have to memorize that lesson to
Recite it to the teacher.
Be ready to recite it to the teacher on Wednesday.
You have to do it every day like that.
So it's getting through your brain.
So you can't get the day, huh?
No way.
Well, it's like, keeps you on your feet.
Yeah.
See, the homework, we have homework too, but we have to recite it, what he teaches us.
You know, he'll call me, and then he'll give me.
If you don't remember anything, that's a zero.
We have more competition.
At the end of each month, we vote for who is the best student.
And it's boys and girls in the classroom, right?
I would think it's not as social as I think it is here in America.
No, it's not as social.
It's not?
What is it like?
What do young people do in Vietnam?
You mean after 75 or before?
No, I mean like after school?
After school, they go home and have the parents out.
Where are your parents now?
Are they in Dallas?
And what does your father do now?
He's an electrical technician.
And your mother?
She's a tailor.
Do you think they've changed since they've been here?
Not very much.
Do they still like to go back to Vietnam?
So, when you have children, would you like them to...
I would assume that most likely they'd be born in America, the children, but would you want them to know Vietnam?
Sure, I would raise them to Vietnamese language.
What is that?
Let them know, you know, try to let them speak Vietnamese, learn to write, and know about our culture, our history.
Sure, that's important.
Yeah.
Well, I think...
I don't think there's anything else.
I can't think of anything.
Did you look at other schools before you came to A&M?
No, UT and Rice.
And you didn't like A&M?
Rice was too much for me.
I can't afford it.
But UT, I don't like it.
You don't like it?
How come?
I don't know.
I just don't know.
No?
Too many people?
Or just the school?
Just the school.
So do you have to pay for school yourself?
Or are you a parent?
No, I got a power bank and I work to support myself.
I bet that's hard though, going to work and school at the same time.
Because I know, I'm an only child and my parents totally, fully support me.
And I have a lot of friends that work and go to school.
And I have a friend who works and he goes to school.
You know, he has to support himself totally.
And I know that would be really hard.
You know, that's very stressful.
Do you think it's a lot of stress?
Yes, it is.
It adds.
Especially if you have a family.
I know I have a couple friends that I will marry and try to go to school and support themselves.
Do you have to help out your family at the same time?
No, no.
Okay, it worked.
